Grey's Anatomy is a medical drama television show that focuses on a certain group of doctors in the Grey Sloan Memorial Hospital, previously known as Seattle Grace Hospital. Some pros are that this show really gets the audience attached to certain characters and Shonda Rhimes the creator and writer always keeps you on the edge of your seat. Merideth the main character in the series and her husband Derek Shepard go through many struggles to maintain relationships with their co workers. Grey's is a nonstop nail biter because you never know what will happen next and who will come into the hospital or what doctor will die next because Shondra loves to do that to you. The show also helps you understand some medical terms and how to do basic things if you watch the show enough. I know know that a healthy persons BP is 120/80.

Some Cons on the show is that you cannot get too attached to the characters because in the end they all end up leaving the hospital or dying. Shondra makes it really hard for you to not become attached to the characters. Also sometimes the characters will just leave and you do not get any explanation as to where they went. For example, after her husband died Erica Hahn just stopped showing up on the show and no one ever talks about her anymore so I would really like to know what happened to her and where she is now. Other then that I cannot think of any other problems with the show.

Over all Greys Anatomy is a great show and definitely worth watching if you love to always be kept on the edge of your seat. There is also 13 seasons so you will be watching for a long time unlike some of the other shows that only have 6 or 7 seasons and feel like they are rushed. In Grey's Anatomy nothing is rushed and everything in connected to each somehow.

I came to Grey's Anatomy pretty late and entirely on DVD.  Binge-watching series sets quickly over a matter of days instead of months meant that for me, the rollercoaster ride of the saga of Seattle Grace/Grey Sloan Memorial Hospital and its revolving cast of doctors, nurses, residents and interns was telescoped into a much more intense experience than spooling them out over a period of 12 years.  The show has never been better or more captivating than it was during its first three seasons, when the MAGIC squad of interns (Meredith, Alex, George, Izzy & Christina) were les enfants terribles of surgical medicine in Seattle.  As our interns matured into senior residents with the responsibility of mentoring up-and-coming doctors, the show began to cram in too many incidental/weakly developed characters and began to sacrifice a focus on medical drama at the expense of way too much focus on the sexploits of interchangeable interns who all looked and acted like over-caffeinated high school AP science geeks having a 'Work Experience'.  Chyler Leigh's Lexie Grey, introduced in Season 4 was a rare exception.  Mer's half-sister added some zest to the proceedings before perishing in the plane crash that also killed her colleague and sometime love interest Dr. Mark Sloan (the McSteamy Eric Dane) and prompted a change in the name of our titular medical center.

Despite the overall mediocrity of many of the storylines from Season 4 onwards, Shonda Rimes and her writing team could always be relied upon to have a few standout episodes/arcs in each season that would keep me hooked, even as I groaned at the other not-great parts.  After the conclusion of Season 11, I was ready to give up entirely on this show.  I was not a particular Patrick Dempsey/McDreamy fan; a large percentage of the time I thought Derek was a colossal donkey's butt.  But there were redeeming qualities, besides the Hair to him.  For better or for worse, the saga of MerDer was the anchor of this show and it seemed like removing Derek Shepard from this equation would be a fatal blow to the series.  There is still a feeling of emptiness on account of his loss, not to mention all the other characters that have left us through various tragedies and personal crises.  I threw a party when D-Izzy decamped the scene, but remain inconsolable about the loss of George (T.R. Knight).  Callie Torres (Sara Ramirez) was a much more likeable character when she was still attracted to men, in my opinion.  The ensuing CalZona drama after Callie discovered her calling to GyrrlNation has become one of the more tedious elements of this series.  Along with the tedious, repetitive drama represented by Jackson & April and their endless bickering.  They are an illustration of just why missionary dating is a project doomed for abject failure if ever there was one.

In Season 12, though there are additional helpings of the same recycled tedium that we've had before, there are some bright spots to be found.  Dr Miranda Bailey (Chandra Wilson) the 4'11" powerhouse that has been inspiring fear and awe in interns, residents, her peers AND her bosses since 2004 finally gets her due and becomes the Chief of Surgery.  There is a good storyline for her as she juggles being a wife with being her husband's boss.  There will be Blood.  My personal crumpet, the most unlikely sex object since Hugh Laurie's House, Dr. Owen Hunt (Kevin McKidd) is back, and despite the decamping of his ex, Cristina, is getting more lady action than anyone else in the hospital, including the lesbians.  Mr. McKidd (a prolific episode director and a Scot) is joined by another foreign-born, tasty crumpet, Martin Henderson ('Bride & Prejudice', a Kiwi.)  Henderson's Dr. Riggs, a former Army buddy of Owen's presents fresh meat for the badgers of Grey Sloan to chew over, and presents a possible route out of widowhood status for Mer.

To cut a long story short--this season is, while far from the series' dramatic peak, much better than I was prepared for.  This is due to a large degree to the focus pulling back from Meredith, and giving more equal screen time to the other characters.  It's still 'Grey's Anatomy' but Ellen Pompeo is more of an ensemble player now.  This is to the good; I have always felt that Pompeo's range as an actress was not on a par with many of her co-stars.  To me Meredith/Pompeo is very like Carrie Bradshaw/Sarah Jessica Parker on Sex and the City:  heading a large cast as the 'star', she is far less appealing or attractive a character than the supporting players surrounding her, and exudes a near toxic level of thoughtless narcissism.  The loss of the MerDer show has meant that other characters get to stretch their wings from out under its shadow.  Based on this season, this show could potentially run for a while yet, though a merciful wrap-up would not be a premature idea.

Greys Anatomy: The Complete Twelfth Season is a 6-disc DVD set containing 24 full, uncut episodes. The cast includes Ellen Pompeo (Meredith Grey), Justin Chambers (Alex Karev), Chandra Wilson (Miranda Bailey), James Pickens, Jr. (Richard Webber), Sara Ramirez (Callie Torres), Kevin McKidd (Owen Hiunt), Jessica Capshaw (Arizona Robbins), Jesse Williams (Jackson Avery), Sarah Drew (April Kepner), and Caterina Scorsone (Amelia Shepherd).

Season twelve episodes involve some of the doctors revisiting the effects of bullying on their pasts, Meredith adjusting to changes at home with her new roommate,  Bailey tackling her first day as Chief,  Amelia working out her relationship with Owen, Owen suggesting how interns should break bad news to patients families, a dinner party gone bad, Miranda forming an advisory committee to recommend disciplinary action against Ben, saving the life of a boy whos been shot, and Callie and Arizona continuing to struggle with the custody arrangement.

Greys Anatomy premiered on ABC on March 27, 2005. The series is set in Seattle at the Grey-Sloan Memorial Hospital and focuses on the lives of surgical interns, residents, and attending physicians as they gradually evolve into experienced doctors, while trying to maintain personal lives and relationships. The show received the 2007 Golden Globe Award for Best Television Series - Drama and received multiple Emmy nominations. It is the longest running scripted primetime show currently airing on ABC and the second longest scripted primetime show ever on ABC, behind only The Adventures of Ozzie and Harriet.

Bonus features include deleted scenes and bloopers.

I really can't even give this season more stars because it wwe so awful. I've watched every single episode of the show more than once and am a longterm fan of the show, but s12 took away all my excitement for the show. We all love Meredith, or used to until they changed her personality in season 11, but this huge focus on her when the show also has 15 other series regulars is just not working. How are other characters ever gonna get their storylines to be told well if they don't get the focus they need? I am a huge Alex fan and maybe he and Jo were the characters who were affected by this the most and that's why I'm so bitter about it, but I'm just not happy seeing him get degraded to being the supportive best friend who has nothing going on for himself anymore. It became most evident in the finale when Owen got remarried again (he married Cristina after Alex already got divorced) and when Jackson became a father. Both of them have been on the show half as long as Alex but the writers allow them their own life and they don't have to rush to console Meredith everytime she has a hard time (which let's face it, happens nearly every episode). Plus I'm still not a huge Maggie or Amelia fan and don't like what this show has become ever since Cristina left and they joined. And Penny received way too much attention and development when other characters like Jo could have used that. It was clear from the start that Penny would never stay but we had to watch so much of her and she turned out to be quite the waste of screentime. I just miss equal treamtent of characters this show once had. It became clear last season who Shonda's favorites are and they are the ones who get all the screentime while other characters are suffering.

I used to love this show, but now it's just... well, annoying really. Meredith is too mean, too petty, and too self-important, but I've kind of thought that for a while now. She's never been believable as a mother, but McDreamy balanced it out. With both him and Christina gone, there's nothing even remotely interesting or relatable about her - which is a shame, because she used to be. April is just flat-out annoying, the interns squabble like elementary children, she-Shepherd seems to have zero self-respect, and I no longer see how there's even a remote possibility these characters are actual doctors working in an actual hospital. Pierce is obviously just a substitute for Lexie, and Maggie a poor attempt at replacing Christina as Owen's love interest.

Save yourself the money - don't bother purchasing past season 10, 'cause it's dribble. The last of the great characters left when Christina did, but honestly? Rhimes' first mistake was getting rid of Burke. Then O'Malley. Then Sloan and Lexie. She just capped it off with Christina and Derek. The only true improvement beyond the third season was the departure of Izzie (because Sloan and Lexie weren't improvements, they were legacies in the making that became part of the heart of GA).

And I guess that's what is missing in the last two seasons - heart. Seriously, don't bother wasting your money.

They really lost something on this show when they got rid of both Christina and Derek. The women sound whiny, the show has lost its focus and its magic. There was real chemistry between these characters and now there are a lot of characters I just don't care about (April, Maggie, Joe, Amelia) or I find annoying. If Rhimes was going to dramatically change the show then she should have changed it. Instead she keeps the same tone and jingoism but without the characters who made that seem relevant. Maggie's "OMG I slept with an intern" is old and she's too old to whine on about it like some teenager. The patient-doctor stories are recycled, the jingoism is recycled and the show lacks enthusiasm. I think Rhimes should just bring it to an end before it totally loses its integrity. I used to really really LOVE this show and I really cared about the characters and now I'm verging on indifference. I found the show on Netflix this summer, and really enjoyed it.  My Dad was very sick, and I spent part of each week with him.  There was alot to do and get used to, and it was a comfort to come home and watch some episodes at night before bed.  I have not seen enough episodes of this season to give the series five stars.  I'm from Maine, and appreciate all Patrick Dempsey has done and does for a nearby hospital.  I definitely miss his character, and I do not review tv shows...this is a first.  The writers have their work cut out for them, as Derek, Christina, Izzy, George, Lexi, and Mark were well written characters given life by very good actors.  Meredith is my favorite, and I love her acting as a Mom...doctor, friend, all her scenes.  Only one story did not ring true for me.  I did not like the way Izzy's storyline ended.  As a viewer who came to the story late, I think the actress had some valid points at the time of her departure.

You may not need McDreamy or you may not need Christina but with both gone the show is bare.  The Dr.s that remain are sophomoric.  The show is currently two dimensional.  I recommend getting season one thru season ten.  Grey's Anatomy was iconic was being the operative word
